{"key":"post-14993826","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>14993826</id>\n<content>The only thing that's really changed is the nomenclature.&amp;nbsp; Coir was used a lot as a 'casing layer' in years past and it always fruited well.&amp;nbsp; Coir/verm is especially good.&amp;nbsp; However, since coir has lots of food for mycelium, it's not really a casing material, but rather a bulk substrate material.&amp;nbsp; The thing to remember is that cubensis doesn't require a casing, fruiting very well from uncased bulk substrates, which is what you really have when using coir.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I hope that makes sense.&amp;nbsp; I've explained it better elsewhere.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>14993864</next>\n<prev>14993798</prev>\n<first>14967890</first>\n<last>14997303</last>\n<when>1314589469</when>\n<utime>08/29/11 06:44 AM</utime>\n</post>"}